04583nam a22006855i 9780824862497DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t19981998hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1054877139  a97808248624977 a10.1515/97808248624972doi  a(DE-B1597)483744  a(OCoLC)1021218724  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aKNQ770b.W35 1998eb 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a346.5105/22211 aWakefield, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFenjia :bHousehold Division and Inheritance in Qing and Republican China /cDavid Wakefield. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[1998] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2 .Inheritance Law and Practice before the Qing -- tChapter 3. Qing Household Division: Why, When, and How? -- tChapter 4 .The Rights of Individuals in Qing Taiwan -- tChapter 5. Dividing Different Types of Property in Qing Taiwan -- tChapter 6 .Household Division Disputes in Qing Courts -- tChapter 7. Republican Rural North China -- tChapter 8. Region and Class: Exceptions, Strategies, and Orientations -- tChapter 9. Household Division and Society: Land, Orientations, and Social Mobility -- tChapter 10 .Conclusions and Speculations -- tAppendix 1. China’s Laws on Inheritance -- tAppendix 2. Historical Sources and Their Limits -- tAppendix 3 .Chinese Terms for Weights and Measures -- tAppendix 4: Chinese Terms for Guarantors on Household Division Documents, by Province -- tAppendix 5: Common Terms for Household Division Documents, by Province0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe division of household property in agricultural societies lies at the centre of the transmission of economic control from one generation to the next. In assembling a body of data concerned with fenjia (household division) in Qing and Republican China, this text investigates one of the central topics in understanding how Chinese society functioned and continues to function. In his presentation of case studies of household division, the author determines that equal division was the rule, yet living parents and single siblings had property rights as well. Variations in inheritance orientations had dramatic effects on landownership patterns, lineage property patterns, lineage strength, class formations and even on state efficiency and its influence on village society. The text explores social class, women and the nuclear family, family documents and law in order to weave the different traditions into a vision of how inheritance, family, lineage and state interacted over the course of Qing and Republican China.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aInheritance and successionzChinaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Packagez978311064968008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311056415040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486249740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824862497423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824862497.jpg  a978-3-11-056415-0  University of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  a978-3-11-064968-0  Asian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Package  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK